{
  "texts": [
    "Some worry that the unreliability of polling results may distort the electoral process, as voters make tactical decisions based on inaccurate information (Dummett 1997).",
    "Even in the absence of misleading information, one might worry that polling results enable tactical voting behaviours-this objection is critically assessed by (Sonderholm 2016).",
    "This concern relies on the assumption that there is something morally questionable in tactical voting as opposed to voting for one's first preference-sometimes called 'sincere voting'.",
    "Against this background, other philosophers have highlighted some virtues of tactical voting.",
    "James Lindley Wilson suggests that it is a way of productively taking into account the views of others (Wilson 2019)-this neatly aligns with the view we defended in the previous section."
  ]
}